   =20
 =20
We  talked yesterday about the ongoing collapse of TerraUSD, or UST, the $1=
8 billion algorithmic stablecoin from Terraform Labs. The basic idea of an =
algorithmic stablecoin is that you can always exchange one UST for $1 worth=
 of Luna, Terraform=E2=80=99s other cryptocurrency, which is meant to guara=
ntee that UST always trades at $1. The risk with this sort of algorithmic s=
tablecoin is that nothing props up the price of=C2=A0Luna, and so if people=
 get worried about UST and try to cash out, they will get $1 worth of Luna,=
 which they will sell, which will drive down the price of Luna, which will =
make people more worried, which will lead more of them to cash out UST and =
sell Luna, which will further drive down the price of Luna, etc., in what i=
s known as a death spiral. Eventually cashing out $1 of UST might get you, =
like, a trillion Luna that no one will want to buy, and the whole thing mig=
ht collapse.When I wrote about this yesterday UST was trading at about $0.5=
3, down about 47% from where it was supposed to be,=C2=A0and Luna was tradi=
ng at about $2.20, down about 93% in 24 hours. Which sounds pretty=C2=A0dea=
th-spirally.=C2=A0And yet it wasn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0that=C2=A0death-spirally. =
Most of the holders of UST had not cashed it in for Luna, in part because t=
he smart contract that turned UST into Luna was moving too slowly to cash o=
ut all the UST holders who wanted out. People were just selling UST on exch=
anges, for prices below $1, and those UST were not being bought by arbitrag=
eurs and transformed into $1 of Luna because the arbitrage mechanism had br=
oken down. Do Kwon, the founder of Terraform Labs and the face of UST and L=
una, tweeted to endorse a plan to print Luna faster so that, you know, the =
death spiral could hurry up. The collapse in UST and Luna prices was not pu=
rely a death spiral happening; rather, it was market prices reflecting trad=
ers=E2=80=99 anticipation of the death spiral.Today, though, things got mor=
e death-spirally. As of 11 a.m.=C2=A0New York time, Luna was trading at abo=
ut $0.013. According to CoinMarketCap data, it peaked at $116.41 in April, =
and was trading above $80 a week ago. It lost 98.7% of its value between la=
st Thursday and yesterday, and then another 98.8% so far today. It is down =
about 99.98% in a week. At $0.013, the market capitalization of Luna =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the total value of all 3.5 billion Luna tokens outstanding =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0was about $45 million.Meanwhile TerraUSD, which had rebounded a bi=
t yesterday,=C2=A0was trading at about $0.49, and there were about 11.9 bil=
lion UST outstanding (down from 18.7 billion last week). People have cashed=
 out almost 7 billion UST for Luna, which increased the supply of Luna from=
 about 343 million Luna last week, to about 1.5 billion yesterday, to about=
 3.5 billion this morning.[3] This increased supply, and the accompanying l=
oss of confidence,=C2=A0drove the price of Luna down by=C2=A099.98% in a we=
ek.Meanwhile there is still 11.9 billion UST remaining, which in theory cou=
ld be cashed out for $11.9 billion worth of Luna. But as the supply of Luna=
 has ballooned, its total value has fallen to just $45 million. If you trie=
d to cash out 1% of the remaining UST =E2=80=94=C2=A0$119 million of face v=
alue =E2=80=94=C2=A0you would get back something like 9 billion Luna, more =
than double the current amount of Luna outstanding. If you sold those 9 bil=
lion Luna you would not get back $118 million. The price of Luna would drop=
 by another =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I do not have a precise number here, but let=E2=
=80=99s estimate that it=E2=80=99s a two-digit percentage where the first d=
igit is a 9, and the second digit is a 9, and probably some of the digits a=
fter the decimal point are also 9s. That=E2=80=99s if you cashed out one pe=
rcent=C2=A0of the remaining UST. Then you=E2=80=99d have to cash out the ot=
her 99%. That=E2=80=99s a death spiral.Elsewhere in Terra and Luna:=09I hav=
e mostly been writing about this story on the conceptual level of the algor=
ithmic stablecoin mechanics (and death spirals), but, again, the drop in Te=
rraUSD started not so much as a death spiral (redeeming UST for Luna, selli=
ng Luna, etc.) but rather as market trades that anticipated=C2=A0(or bet=C2=
=A0on, or tried to cause) a death spiral. There is a fair amount of conspir=
acy theorizing about who was doing these trades and why, but there is also =
some good analysis of what actually happened. Here, for instance, is a look=
 at=C2=A0the order books for UST on different crypto exchanges.=C2=A0=09Mea=
nwhile on the conspiracy theories: People on Twitter have sometimes pointed=
 to Citadel Securities and, for some reason, BlackRock Inc. as the shadowy =
figures behind UST=E2=80=99s collapse. They have   denied it. Citadel Secur=
ities =E2=80=9Cdoes not trade stablecoins, including UST,=E2=80=9D and=C2=
=A0=E2=80=9CBlackRock does not trade UST,=E2=80=9D their spokespeople said.=
 For the record (1) I believe them but (2) I would laugh a lot if Citadel S=
ecurities was in fact behind the trade that broke UST.=C2=A0(I would be ver=
y confused if it was BlackRock.)=C2=A0=09There is a Swiss=C2=A0exchange-tra=
ded product linked to Luna? Oops! You can imagine  how that=E2=80=99s going=
.=09CoinDesk  reports that =E2=80=9CDo Kwon, the CEO of Terra creator Terra=
form Labs, was one of the pseudonymous co-founders behind the failed algori=
thmic stablecoin Basis Cash.=E2=80=9D Third time=E2=80=99s the charm, maybe=
. Kwon hasn=E2=80=99t tweeted since yesterday morning (New York time),  whe=
n he said =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re here to stay. And we=E2=80=99re gonna keep=
 making noise.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
