What a weird deal:Elon Musk is in talks to raise enough equity and preferre=
d financing for his proposed buyout of Twitter Inc. to eliminate the need f=
or any margin loan linked to his Tesla Inc. shares, according to people wit=
h knowledge of the matter.=C2=A0The billionaire=E2=80=99s advisers, led by =
Morgan Stanley, have begun soliciting interest from potential investors for=
 as much as $6 billion in preferred equity financing, the people said, aski=
ng not to be named discussing a private transaction. =E2=80=A6The preferred=
 equity may have a 20-year maturity and include a feature allowing interest=
 to be paid in kind at a rate of 14%, the people said. That interest rate w=
ould be increased by 75 basis points in the seventh, eight and ninth year, =
they added. The financing may alternatively be structured with a 10% intere=
st rate and warrants, one of the people said.=C2=A0I can definitely see why=
 he would want to get rid of the margin loan. If he gets  the margin loan, =
he has to pay interest on it every year, in cash, himself; he=E2=80=99d be =
making continuing payments for the privilege of owning Twitter. Whereas if =
he raises debt, or preferred stock,=C2=A0at Twitter, that=E2=80=99s Twitter=
=E2=80=99s problem; he doesn=E2=80=99t have to keep shelling out cash just =
to own Twitter. Of course if he eliminates the margin loan he is still on t=
he hook to contribute something like $20 billion of equity to the Twitter b=
uyout, meaning that he still has to come up with $20 billion of cash at clo=
sing, and arguably Musk=E2=80=99s opportunity cost (and taxes!) of selling =
$20 billion of Tesla stock to raise that money is higher than the interest =
on the margin loan. Still, if he sells Tesla stock, it=E2=80=99s done; if h=
e margins his Tesla stock, that creates a continuing overhang.I have a hard=
er time understanding a 14% pay-in-kind preferred? At Twitter? Musk=E2=80=
=99s buyout plans for Twitter already involve $13 billion of high-yield deb=
t with  an interest cost of, in rough numbers, all of Twitter=E2=80=99s cas=
h flow in the near future. There is certainly not enough money left over to=
 pay a 14% cash dividend on $6 billion of preferred stock. So you just accr=
ue it up; in three years $6=C2=A0billion of preferred turns into $9 billion=
; in seven years it=E2=80=99s $15 billion. If he sells Twitter for a lot mo=
re than he paid for it, the preferred gets paid and he makes money. If he s=
ells Twitter for less than he paid for it, the preferred gets paid before h=
e does, though after the $13 billion of debt. Buying this preferred is esse=
ntially a bet that Elon Musk will do=C2=A0okay=C2=A0with Twitter: If it=E2=
=80=99s a disaster, you lose everything, and if it=E2=80=99s a huge success=
, you=E2=80=99d rather just own regular equity.[4] I feel like =E2=80=9Cdis=
aster=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Chuge success=E2=80=9D are the main Elon Musk ou=
tcomes, making this kind of a strange bet.Elsewhere, Musk might do the thin=
g where he takes Twitter private but somehow allows small retail shareholde=
rs to keep their stock? I mean, not really, but  here=E2=80=99s this:Some p=
otential investors -- including hedge funds and wealthy individuals -- have=
 been pitched the opportunity to invest $5 million or more in the Twitter b=
uyout, according to people with knowledge of the matter. They=E2=80=99re be=
ing invited to commit money through special-purpose vehicles that will pool=
 capital together from a variety of smaller sources, the people said.=C2=A0=
One party canvassing investors is seeking to collect $500 million in total,=
 and plans to charge a 5% fee to whoever it brings in. The move could allow=
 a well-connected financier to rope in investors who might not have direct =
access to the deal, but nonetheless want to join one of the biggest leverag=
ed buyouts in history. =E2=80=A6Getting into the deal through one of these =
side funds isn=E2=80=99t being sanctioned by Musk, according to a person fa=
miliar with the matter. Musk=E2=80=99s existing equity investment agreement=
s have been structured to forbid investors from raising a special purpose v=
ehicle, the person said. If investors do participate in them, they risk los=
ing their shares, the person said.Still, Musk is open to smaller investors =
getting involved and has already agreed to accept checks from as low as $5 =
million, a filing showed last week.Yeah I mean I can see why you=E2=80=99d =
go around pitching that, even if Musk has explicitly forbidden it.
