      Chicken Box for the Soul
   =20
 =20
 Yeesh:Chicken Soup for the Soul Entertainment Inc. has acquired Redbox Ent=
ertainment Inc., a movies-to-rent streaming service that went public throug=
h a blank-check company last year, another sign that once-booming SPACs and=
 the deals they fueled are losing steam.The acquisition is valued at about =
$31 million, according to data compiled by Bloomberg, a huge markdown from =
the $254 million valuation Redbox had traded for before the deal was announ=
ced Wednesday. Chicken Soup has agreed to take on about $321 million in Red=
box debt and got the company a new term loan.=C2=A0As part of the all-stock=
 transaction, shareholders of Redbox will receive 0.087 of Chicken Soup=E2=
=80=99s Class A common stock per share. Apollo Global Management, one of th=
e largest backers of Redbox, will own roughly 15.2% of the newly combined e=
ntity while direct lender HPS Partners will own about 4%. The deal is set t=
o close in the second half of 2022.Redbox shares, which plunged as much as =
50% Wednesday, closed down 43% to $3.20 apiece. Since the blank-check deal =
that took the company public, Redbox=E2=80=99s shares have now fallen more =
than 66%, giving it a market value of $145 million.Redbox went public by me=
rging with a special purpose acquisition company in October 2021. As is tra=
ditional in a SPAC deal, Redbox essentially went public at $10 per share. A=
fter the deal, Redbox traded as high as $17.93 per share, for a market capi=
talization of about $1 billion. Then it all kind of fell apart. =E2=80=9CDu=
ring 2021, Redbox Entertainment Inc.=E2=80=99s (=E2=80=98Redbox=E2=80=99) b=
usiness was negatively impacted by the effects of the ongoing COVID-19 pand=
emic, which resulted in fewer releases on its platforms than management pre=
viously expected and materially lower financial results,=E2=80=9D it announ=
ced in February. (Remember it went public in October 2021; what=C2=A0did=C2=
=A0they expect 2021 results to be like at that point?) By Tuesday, the stoc=
k was at $5.60, for a market cap of just $254 million.=C2=A0And then Redbox=
 went and sold itself to Chicken Soup for $31 million? Each Redbox share, w=
hich traded at $5.60 on Tuesday, will be exchanged for 0.087 Chicken Soup s=
hares, which traded at $7.92=C2=A0on Tuesday, for a merger value of about $=
0.69 per share, an 88% discount to the pre-merger price. Ordinarily when on=
e company acquires another it pays a premium, though in an all-stock merger=
 of equals (which this is not really) there might be no premium. A merger a=
t a discount =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Ctake-under=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0i=
s rare. A merger at an 88% discount is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t know,=
 Bear Stearns comes to mind?[5]When they read the announcement, people appa=
rently thought the exchange ratio might be a typo. Selling Redbox for 0.87 =
Chicken Soup shares worth about $6.89, a 23% premium to Redbox=E2=80=99s ba=
ttered stock price, would be kinda normal. But, no, it=E2=80=99s 0.087. At =
11 a.m. Redbox was trading at $2.58, basically in disbelief, while Chicken =
Soup was at $6.17, giving an implied deal value of $0.49.I don=E2=80=99t kn=
ow! The implication here seems to be that Redbox was basically running out =
of money and this deal rescued it from that fate[6]; it=E2=80=99s bad=C2=A0=
for shareholders, but better than the alternative, and at least they get to=
 participate in the upside (via Chicken Soup stock) if things get better. =
=E2=80=9CRedbox stockholders holding approximately 86% of the Redbox voting=
 power have entered into a voting agreement to approve the transaction,=E2=
=80=9D so if you are a retail shareholder who bought the SPAC stock and are=
 unhappy about this deal there is not a lot you can do about it. You could =
probably sell at $2.58 before the deal closes at $0.49 though.
