10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong><em> Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p><table class=3D"header" =
width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Crypto</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2008 the prices of some structured =
credit products built out of subprime U.S. mortgages went down, and as a re=
sult there was a global recession and millions of people lost their jobs. I=
f you had asked a normal person in 2007: =E2=80=9CHow would it affect your =
life if it turns out that investors have mispriced the super-senior risk in=
 synthetic collateralized debt obligations built out of subprime mortgage t=
ranches,=E2=80=9D that person would have said =E2=80=9CI have no idea what =
you are talking about, but I can=E2=80=99t imagine how that collection of w=
ords would affect me.=E2=80=9D But it did. Loosely speaking,[1] the mechani=
sm was that the people (often banks or shadow banks) who owned subprime CDO=
s (1) also owned other stuff and (2) had borrowed money to buy that stuff. =
When their CDOs collapsed, they had to sell other stuff to pay off their de=
bts, which drove down the prices of other stuff, which led to broad market =
contagion, which destroyed a lot of wealth, which reduced economic activity=
, etc. Meanwhile the banks had lost money and were more risk-averse and les=
s able to lend, which also reduced economic activity. And so normal people =
lost their jobs because of contagion from some weird financial asset that t=
hey hadn=E2=80=99t even heard of.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you as=
ked a normal person, you know, two weeks ago: =E2=80=9CHow would it affect =
your=C2=A0life if the prices of some monkey JPEGs and algorithmic stablecoi=
ns crash,=E2=80=9D I think most people would reasonably have said =E2=80=9C=
I do not own a monkey JPEG and do not aspire to own one, so this will not a=
ffect me at all.=E2=80=9D My=C2=A0<em>guess=C2=A0</em>is that they would ha=
ve been right. My=C2=A0<em>guess=C2=A0</em>is that the real world is not=C2=
=A0<em>too=C2=A0</em>affected by the crypto world, and that if crypto price=
s crash there will not be a ton of contagion in the rest of the financial s=
ystem. But I think it is, at this point, debatable. Crypto has at least sta=
rted to work its way into the real financial system. Some traditional inves=
tors also own crypto; if their crypto goes down they might have to sell reg=
ular stuff. Some public companies are exposed to crypto (because they <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27692123.259606/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTEvY29pbmJhc2UtdH=
VtYmxlcy10by1yZWNvcmQtbG93cy1hcy1jcnlwdG8tbWVsdGRvd24tZGVlcGVucz9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQwNTEyMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB01e086e8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> are crypto exchanges</a>, because they have <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27692123.259606/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmFycm9ucy5jb20vYXJ0aWNsZXMvbWljcm9zdHJhdGVneS1zdG9jay1jcnVtYmxpbmc=
tYml0Y29pbi1zbGlkZXMtcmF0ZXMtcmlzZS01MTY1MjExNzY1NT9tb2Q9U2VhcmNocmVzdWx0cw=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdc65aac9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">levered crypto holdings</a>, et=
c.), so your boring old index fund might go down when crypto goes down.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ten years ago, if you had waved a magic wand a=
nd every cryptocurrency went to zero, not much would have happened. A few o=
ddballs experimenting with a newfangled money called Bitcoin would have see=
n their experiment fail. =E2=80=9COh well, that was cool for a while,=E2=80=
=9D they would have said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Five years ago, i=
f every cryptocurrency went to zero, a lot of people would have lost a lot =
of money. But they would mostly be <em>crypto people:=C2=A0</em>Some indivi=
duals and some hedge funds that bought crypto would lose their money. The c=
ontagion to the real financial system would have been small. Lamborghini de=
alerships would have a rough year. But most people would barely notice.</p>=
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Five years from now, if every cryptocurrency g=
oes to zero =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, I don=E2=80=99t know what the next five ye=
ars will be like, but a plausible story (as of last week anyway!) is that t=
here will be continuing integration of crypto into the real economy. More c=
rypto companies will be big and important and intertwined with other compan=
ies; their stock will be in the indexes and they will borrow money from ban=
ks and use their own money to finance real businesses. More traditional inv=
estors will own crypto, and will make levered bets on crypto, and if those =
bets blow up they will naturally sell more liquid traditional assets, causi=
ng contagion from crypto markets to stock and bond markets. Crypto platform=
s will be used for real economic activity; ordinary people will invest thei=
r savings in those platforms, and those investments will be used to finance=
 real, non-crypto business activity. You=E2=80=99ll get your mortgage from =
a decentralized finance platform or whatever.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">This is a very=C2=A0<em>bullish=C2=A0</em>story for crypto; in this stor=
y, broad institutional adoption and growing utility will be good for the po=
pularity, and prices, of crypto. And then if there=E2=80=99s a break in cry=
pto =E2=80=94=C2=A0if there=E2=80=99s a run on a stablecoin, if there=E2=80=
=99s a rug-pull in a popular DeFi project, if <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/27692123.259606/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudmljZS5jb20vZW4=
vYXJ0aWNsZS95M3YzbnkvYWxsLW15LWFwZXMtZ29uZS1uZnQtdGhlZnQtdmljdGltcy1iZWctZm=
9yLWNlbnRyYWxpemVkLXNhdmlvcnM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB68dbd648" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
all the apes gone</a> =E2=80=94 that break will naturally spread to the bro=
ader financial system, and that will be a sign of crypto=E2=80=99s <em>succ=
ess</em>. Ideally there would not be a lot of breaks; that would also be a =
sign of success. But a sign of=C2=A0<em>failure=C2=A0</em>would be if crypt=
o projects keep blowing up and nobody outside of those projects notices. Th=
at would be a sign that crypto isn=E2=80=99t good for anything, that it can=
not provide benefits to the real world. If crypto can be good for the real =
world, then crypto prices going down should be bad for the real world.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Right now we are probably in between? Crypto ha=
s been <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27692123.25=
9606/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTIvbW=
9yZS10aGFuLTIwMC1iaWxpb24td2lwZWQtb2ZmLWNyeXB0b2N1cnJlbmN5LW1hcmtldC1pbi1hL=
WRheT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTEyMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3Vy=
Y2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA1MTImdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9dac1b5a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> having a horrible time</a>:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A massive sell-off in cryptocurrencie=
s wiped over $200 billion of wealth from the market in just 24 hours, accor=
ding to estimates from price-tracking website CoinMarketCap.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">The broad plunge in the crypto complex, driven by the col=
lapse of the TerraUSD stablecoin, hit major tokens hard. Bitcoin plunged by=
 as much as 10% in the last day to its lowest level since Dec. 2020, while =
Ethereum dropped as much as 16%.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">And there does seem to be=C2=A0some worry about contagion to broader mar=
kets, at least through the transmission vector of=C2=A0retail meme traders.=
 Bloomberg=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/27692123.259606/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjItMDUtMTIvY3J5cHRvLXN0cmVzcy1pcy1mZWVkaW5nLXRoZS13aWRlci1zZWxsb2ZmLW=
luLWdsb2JhbC1tYXJrZXRzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTIyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09Z=
W1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDUxMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249=
bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91ab0095" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Lynn Thomasson an=
d Anchalee Worrachate report</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">As markets slumped in unison on Thursday, traders pointed to the chaos i=
n crypto as a focal point of their concern. Strategists are increasingly wo=
rried that small traders, already nursing losses from the meme stock craze,=
 will be wiped out on their crypto holdings and sell everything else.=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CContagion here is not via linkage=
s between the crypto ecosystem and the traditional financial system, but vi=
a retail investors sentiment,=E2=80=9D said Nikolaos Panigirtzoglou, global=
 market strategist at JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. =E2=80=9CIf the $1 trillion =
capital loss in crypto markets causes broad-based retrenchment by retail in=
vestors in other risk assets such as equities, then that=E2=80=99s where th=
e spillover is.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=
=9CToday there is a new bear factor that has come into play, namely the col=
lapse in the cryptocurrencies,=E2=80=9D wrote Malcolm Freeman, a director a=
t Kingdom Futures.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CInvestors=
 are getting wiped out in many cases and the question is: Are those investo=
rs also involved in equities? Because if they run for the exit, then metals=
 will take notice and most likely head in the same direction,=E2=80=9D he s=
aid.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27692123.259606/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ=
nQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvNmRjZDAyNjMtZjk3NC00ODMzLTk3YTktOTNiMDViZTc0ZjZl/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBd1c44b04" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Katie Martin notes</a> that =E2=80=9CTy=
pically, what happens in crypto stays in crypto. But big moves can cut thro=
ugh=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One banker tells =
me his hedge fund clients are watching closely now, with several taking ser=
iously the possibility that a big crash in crypto, if it happens, could be =
supportive for that most crucial of markets, US government bonds, again on =
the notion that it would spark a rush to safer places to park cash.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Martin also notes that Tether, the po=
pular stablecoin, which=C2=A0briefly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/27692123.259606/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdz=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMTIvdGV0aGVyLW1vdmVzLXRvLXJlYXNzdXJlLW1hcmtldC1hZnR=
lci1iaWdnZXN0LXN0YWJsZWNvaW4tc2xpcHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUxMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdX=
RtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwNTEyJnV0b=
V9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8e47b6ac" itemprop=3D"=
StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #00000=
0; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-botto=
m-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> los=
t its peg to the dollar</a>, is another potential channel of contagion:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year, rating agency Fitch war=
ned that if tether holders were to fold and seek to flip their tokens into =
real money, then that could destabilise the short-term credit markets where=
 the company says it holds lots of funds.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
=E2=80=9CThe rapid growth of stablecoin issuance could, in time, have impli=
cations for the functioning of short-term credit markets,=E2=80=9D Fitch=E2=
=80=99s analysts said, pointing to =E2=80=9Cpotential asset contagion risks=
 linked to the liquidation of stablecoin reserve holdings=E2=80=9D.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit markets are already wobbling under the pres=
sure of a shift higher in benchmark interest rates. The notion that Tether =
could, if push came to shove, offload chunks of its claimed $24bn stash of =
commercial paper, $35bn hoard of US Treasury bills or $4bn pile of =E2=80=
=9Ccorporate bonds, funds and precious metals=E2=80=9D into these market co=
nditions is potentially unhelpful.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">I make fun of Tether a lot around here, but at a high level you could =
argue that Tether is one of the more important crypto projects in terms of =
having an effect on the real economy. The argument is:</p><ol style=3D"list=
-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">Crypto users want a stablecoin to support their transa=
ctions,=C2=A0gambling, yield farming, etc., and Tether is a popular one.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The way Tether works is that if you =
buy one Tether for a dollar, Tether parks that dollar in some interest-earn=
ing dollar-denominated asset.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In p=
ractice this means making billions of dollars of loans to real companies an=
d financial institutions to finance their businesses.[2]=C2=A0 You know, li=
ke a bank.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Tether thus provides fi=
nancing to the real economy much like a bank does, and because it is =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0regulated differently? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it can perhaps be more nimbl=
e in financing good but risky projects.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">In that model, a run on the Tether bank =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, a run on=
 the crypto bank, on the safe assets of the crypto world=C2=A0=E2=80=94 wou=
ld be bad in much the same way a run on a real bank would be bad, or the wa=
y a run on the 2008 shadow banking system was bad: It would cut back on cre=
dit to real businesses and be bad for the economy.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
